 are from contributors directly engaged in urban Aboriginal communities; they draw on extensive ethnographic research on and by Aboriginal people and their own lived experiences. The interdisciplinary studies of urban Aboriginal community and identity collected in this volume offer narratives of unique experiences and aspects of urban Aboriginal life. They provide innovative perspectives on cultural transformation and continuity and demonstrate how comparative examinations of the diversity within and across urban Aboriginal experiences contribute to broader understandings of the relationship between Aboriginal peoples and the Canadian state and to theoretical debates about power dynamics in the production of community and in processes of identity formation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunity developmentxCanada. 0aCommunity developmentzCanada. 0aIndigenous peoplesxUrban residencezCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 0aNative peoplesxSocial conditionsxCanadaxCanada. 0aNative peoplesxUrban residencexCanada. 0aUrban Indigenous peopleszCanada. 4aIndigenous Studies. 4aSocial Science: Urban Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBrown, Lynda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuddle, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDarnell, Regna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonovan, Sadie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlynn, Lindy-Lou, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Heather A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Heather A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIgnace, Marianne, e